<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-987-122  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 987 122.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Dec 14 1989 v34 n25 p5(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HDTV needs fiber net to survive. (high-definition television)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coco, Donna.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many experts believe that a low-cost, optical-fiber transmissionnetwork extending to the home is a prerequisite to developinghigh-definition television (HDTV) systems.andP;  Fiber-optic networkswould eliminate the need for compression and decompression byproviding greater bandwidth, but they are expensive and will notreach the majority of homes until the year 2010.andP;  Fiber backboneswill offer some improvement over the current network, improvingsignal-to-noise ratios at relatively low cost.andP;  Displaytechnologies are another barrier to HDTV.andP;  Many participants in aseminar on HDTV consider liquid-crystal displays the leadingtechnology for producing large, inexpensive screens; others expectactive-matrix thin-film transistor displays to dominate.andO;Standards and policy issues also impede HDTV in the US.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsHigh-Definition TelevisionNetwork ArchitectureCost Benefit AnalysisForecastingSeminarsCommunications Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>